value.value: A primary or metastatic malignant neoplasm that affects the hard palate, soft palate, or uvula.

An uncommon cause of hypopituitarism seen after severe postpartum hemorrhaging. Prolonged hypovolemia leads to ischemic necrosis of the pituitary. Clinical signs typically present in the puerperium and include failure to begin lactation, fatigue, hypotension and eventual amenorrhea. Clinical course is usually mild, however extreme cases may progress to adrenal failure. Prognosis is most favorable when hormone replacement is initiated soon after symptom onset.

A transient inflammatory pulmonary disorder characterized by eosinophilia. Eosinophilic infiltration of the lungs may be secondary to parasitic infection or drug hypersensitivity. Clinical signs include dry cough, fever and dyspnea. Prognosis is favorable as the disorder follows a self-limited course.
Encephalitis resulting from viral infection.

label.value: Anterolateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

value.value: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads V3 through V6, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the anterolateral wall of the left ventricle. (CDISC)

label.value: Anteroseptal Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

value.value: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads V1 through V4, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the anteroseptal wall of the left ventricle. (CDISC)

label.value: Subendocardial Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

value.value: An electrocardiographic finding of an injury in leads corresponding to the anatomic region of the subendocardial layer of the wall of the heart.
An abnormal growth in the kidney.
A collection of pus that has formed in the axilla.
Dermatitis caused by an allergic reaction to arnica.
Contact dermatitis caused by exposure to acids.
A primary or metastatic malignant neoplasm that affects the pyriform sinus.
Contact dermatitis caused by exposure to alkalis.
Allergic contact dermatitis caused by exposure to dichromate.
Inflammation of the skin resulting from exposure to the sun.
Defective bone growth that affects the growth centers of bone in children.
Abnormal deposits of calcium in the tracheal tissue.
Pneumoconiosis caused by inhalation of kaolin dust.
Inflammation of the lungs caused by the inhalation or aspiration of chemicals.
An impairment of the structure or function of the blood vessels which carry blood away from the heart.
Complete closure of the normally patent lumen of the blood vessels which carry blood away from the heart.
A hemorrhoid which originates above the dentate line.

label.value: Malignant Neoplasm of the Thoracic Esophagus

value.value: A primary or metastatic malignant neoplasm involving the thoracic region of the esophagus.
A hemorrhoid which originates below the dentate line.

A rare genetic disorder with an undetermined pattern of inheritance affecting mostly females. Clinical signs at birth include recurrent respiratory infections, poor feeding, hypotonia, joint laxity and characteristic shortened fifth digits with hypoplastic or absent nails and craniofacial appearance: microcephaly, wide nose and lips, sparse scalp hair but thick eyebrows and eyelashes. The clinical course includes developmental delays in motor skills and speech with associated moderate mental retardation.
An abnormally increased curvature of the thoracic portion of the spine that is present at the time of birth.
A chronic inflammatory process that affects the tissues that surround and support the teeth.
An abnormal connection between a bronchus and the esophagus.
Trauma to the esophagus.
Crohn's disease affecting the ileum.

label.value: Malignant Neoplasm of the Upper Third of the Esophagus

value.value: A primary or metastatic malignant neoplasm involving the upper third segment of the esophagus.
Gastroenteritis that is characterized by eosinophilic infiltration.
Acute inflammation of the liver.
An acute or chronic inflammation of the gallbladder associated with the presence of gallstones.
A concretion in the cystic duct.
Cholangitis that is both sudden in onset and of a relatively short duration.
Cholangitis that is persistent and long-standing.
Cholangitis that is characterized by pyogenic organisms.
A rare autosomal recessive inherited nephrotic syndrome that is present in the first week of life. It manifests with edema and proteinuria and usually has a poor prognosis.
A non-neoplastic kidney disorder that results from the damage of the renal arteries or veins. It may lead to renal dysfunction and/or hypertension.
The uterus has descended above the hymen.

label.value: Malignant Neoplasm of the Middle Third of the Esophagus

value.value: A primary or metastatic malignant neoplasm involving the middle third segment of the esophagus.
The uterus has descended to the level of the hymen.
A disorder of the neural pathway from the optic nerve to the visual cortex.

A state of bone marrow suppression and failure that is caused by a cytotoxic or adverse immunologic response to a drug treatment, leading to a failure of production of red blood cells, white cells and platelets.
A condition characterized by the presence of a variant of normal hemoglobin (hemoglobin D), which is caused by mutation(s) in the gene encoding the beta subunit of the hemoglobin molecule.
